# Budget Buddy — Cursor Rules

## Project Overview

A personal budget calendar app called "Budget Buddy". Mobile-first PWA built with Next.js App Router, Tailwind CSS, shadcn/ui, and Supabase.

## Tech Stack

- Next.js 16 with App Router
- Tailwind CSS v4 (no tailwind.config.ts — configured via CSS variables in app/globals.css)
- shadcn/ui components in components/ui/
- Supabase for auth and database
- SWR for client-side data fetching
- TypeScript throughout
- date-fns for date manipulation
- Lucide React for icons
- react-swipeable for swipe gesture handling

## Supabase Schema

### accounts

- id: uuid (primary key)
- user_id: uuid (references auth.users)
- name: text
- starting_balance: numeric
- created_at: timestamptz

### transactions

- id: uuid (primary key)
- user_id: uuid (references auth.users)
- account_id: uuid (references accounts)
- label: text
- amount: numeric (negative for expenses, positive for income)
- date: date (format: yyyy-MM-dd)
- category_id: uuid (nullable, references categories)
- created_at: timestamptz

### recurring_rules

- id: uuid (primary key)
- user_id: uuid (references auth.users)
- account_id: uuid (references accounts)
- label: text
- amount: numeric (negative for expenses, positive for income)
- frequency: text (weekly | biweekly | monthly | yearly)
- start_date: date (format: yyyy-MM-dd)
- end_date: date (nullable)
- root_rule_id: uuid (nullable, references recurring_rules — root row has null; split segments point at the chain root id)
- category_id: uuid (nullable, references categories)
- created_at: timestamptz

Chain: root has `root_rule_id = null`; splits have `root_rule_id = original_root_id`. Query all segments with `id = rootId OR root_rule_id = rootId`, ordered by `start_date`.

### recurring_exceptions

- id: uuid (primary key)
- user_id: uuid (references auth.users)
- rule_id: uuid (references recurring_rules)
- exception_date: date (format: yyyy-MM-dd)
- type: text ('skip' | 'modified')
- modified_amount: numeric (nullable — only used when type = 'modified')
- modified_label: text (nullable — only used when type = 'modified')
- category_id: uuid (nullable, references categories — optional override for type = 'modified')
- created_at: timestamptz

### categories

- id: uuid (primary key)
- user_id: uuid (references auth.users)
- account_id: uuid (references accounts)
- name: text
- icon: text (icon name from ALLOWED_CATEGORY_ICON_NAMES in components/category-icons.tsx)
- type: text ('expense' | 'income')
- created_at: timestamptz

### account_members

- id: uuid (primary key)
- account_id: uuid (references accounts ON DELETE CASCADE)
- user_id: uuid (references auth.users ON DELETE CASCADE)
- role: text ('owner' | 'member')
- invited_by: uuid (nullable, references auth.users)
- created_at: timestamptz
- UNIQUE (account_id, user_id)

### budget_invitations

- id: uuid (primary key)
- account_id: uuid (references accounts ON DELETE CASCADE)
- invited_by: uuid (references auth.users ON DELETE CASCADE)
- invited_email: text (always lowercased; DB CHECK constraint enforces this)
- token: uuid (unique, generated by DB)
- expires_at: timestamptz (default now() + 7 days)
- accepted_at: timestamptz (nullable)
- created_at: timestamptz
- Partial unique index on (account_id, invited_email) WHERE accepted_at IS NULL — prevents duplicate active invites

## Supabase Client Usage

- Browser/client components: import { createClient } from "@/lib/supabase/client"
- Server components: import { createClient } from "@/lib/supabase/server" (always await it)
- Never use the service_role key — only anon key in frontend code (service role is used only in `lib/member-actions.ts` and `lib/invite-actions.ts`, which are `"use server"` files)
- RLS handles row-level access — do not add redundant client-side `user_id` WHERE filters to queries on account-scoped tables (transactions, recurring_rules, categories, recurring_exceptions). Those filters were removed as part of budget-sharing: keeping them silently broke cross-member edits. `user_id` is still written on INSERT rows where the column exists. `account_members` queries do filter by `user_id` to fetch the current user's own membership rows.
- Default to SWR + browser client for new pages

## Architecture Rules

- The app uses SWR for client-side data fetching via lib/api.ts
- fetchCalendarData(month, year, accountId) and fetchTransactions(accountId) are the two main data fetching functions (used with useSWR). fetchAccounts() returns the user's full account list for the picker. fetchCategories(accountId) scopes categories to the active budget. fetchPendingInvitations(accountId) returns pending invites for the budget owner's Members UI.
- Mutations use the Supabase browser client (lib/supabase/client.ts) and call mutate() from SWR after success to invalidate cache
- mutate() is the primary cache invalidation method — not router.refresh()
- Auth protection: root `proxy.ts` (Next.js 16 proxy convention — not `middleware.ts`; edge redirects for `/login` vs app routes)
- Transaction, recurring rule, and account mutations all live in lib/transactions-mutations.ts — never inline these in components. Settings auto-saves the active budget's name/starting balance (debounced 1s) via `updateAccount`; category CRUD still uses explicit dialog actions.
- Active budget context: `components/active-account-provider.tsx` exposes `useActiveAccount()` (mounted in `app/(app)/layout.tsx` inside a `<Suspense>`). Resolution order on mount: `?account=<uuid>` URL param (read-only input) → localStorage key `budget-buddy:active-account` → first account in the list. The picker writes to localStorage only — it never pushes the active id to the URL. `setActiveAccount(id)` must ignore ids not present in the loaded `accounts` list. Pages that already manage URL state (calendar, /add) may include `?account=` on outbound deep links so back-navigation and cross-device opens restore the intended budget.
- All app reads (calendar, transactions, analytics, day sheet, /add) MUST scope queries by the active account: pass `activeAccountId` to fetchers, gate SWR keys with `activeAccountId ? ... : null` so we never fetch unscoped, and include `accountId` in cache keys.
- After any mutation, invalidate SWR cache appropriately (always include accountId where keys are account-scoped):
  - One-time transaction create/update/delete: `mutate(transactionsSwrKey(accountId))` plus `mutate(calendarMonthSwrKey(txMonth, txYear, accountId))`
  - Recurring rule mutations (edit, skip, delete): `invalidateNext12CalendarMonths(accountId)` from lib/swr-invalidate.ts; on the calendar home also call `mutate(calendarMonthSwrKey(month, year, accountId))` to cover the visible month when it's a past month outside the next-12 window
  - Category mutations: `mutate(categoriesSwrKey(accountId))` only
  - Active-budget settings save (auto, debounced): `mutate(accountsSwrKey)` + `mutate(transactionsSwrKey(accountId))` + `mutate(calendarMonthSwrKey(currentMonth, currentYear, accountId))`
  - Account create / rename: `mutate(accountsSwrKey)`. After a create, immediately switch active account to the new id via `setActiveAccount(newId)` so the user lands on the new budget.
- Home calendar URL (`app/(app)/page.tsx`): optional `?month=` (1–12) and `?year=` (1900–2100); invalid or missing query values fall back to the current month/year; optional `?selected=` (`yyyy-MM-dd`, validated) pre-selects that day and aligns the visible month (e.g. after save from `/add`). Tapping a day in `components/calendar-view.tsx` calls `router.replace` with `month`, `year`, and `selected` so `router.back()` from `/add` restores selection.
- Calendar home: while `useActiveAccount().isLoading` (accounts fetch + active-id hydration), show pulse placeholders for the budget picker row and balance strip only; `CalendarGrid` uses its normal skeleton (`isLoading`) so the page layout matches pre-hydration UX instead of a blank full-screen gate.

## Design System

- Font: Inter (--font-sans in @theme inline)
- CSS variables (:root): --background (#f0f4f8), --foreground (#0f172a), --card (#ffffff), --card-foreground (#0f172a), --popover, --popover-foreground, --primary (#4f6bed), --primary-foreground (#ffffff), --secondary (#f1f5f9), --secondary-foreground, --muted (#f1f5f9), --muted-foreground (#64748b), --accent (#eef2ff), --accent-foreground (#4f6bed), --destructive (#dc2626), --destructive-foreground, --success (#16a34a), --success-foreground, --amount-positive (#4ade80), --amount-negative (#e11d48), --border (#e2e8f0), --input, --ring (#4f6bed), --radius (1rem)
- CSS layout variables: --nav-height (56px), --nav-bottom (0px), --fab-gap (12px)
- Tailwind color tokens: bg-background, bg-card, text-foreground, text-muted-foreground, text-primary, border-border, etc. (mapped in @theme inline)
- Glass utilities: .glass, .glass-card (blur); .nav-opaque (solid primary nav); .text-overlay, .amount-text (text shadows on glass). Calendar cells use inline Tailwind classes in calendar-grid.tsx — no custom CSS classes
- Animation classes: .animated-gradient (gradientShift keyframes); .wave-emoji (wave-on-load); .greeting-enter, .account-enter, .balance-card-1/2/3, .calendar-enter, .page-enter-1 through .page-enter-5, .transaction-group-enter (greetingEnter); .calendar-slide-from-left, .calendar-slide-from-right (month-change slide)

## Component Rules

components/ui/ contains shadcn primitives that you own and can modify.

- Edit components/ui/ directly for global changes that should affect all usages (e.g. adding tap states to all buttons)
- Use className overrides at the usage site for context-specific styling (e.g. white text only on glass backgrounds)
- Always add a comment when editing a shadcn component so changes are easy to identify if the component is ever re-added via shadcn CLI
- Never make broad changes to components/ui/ without explicit instruction — always review diffs carefully

- Icons: always use lucide-react
- Amount display: always use Math.abs(amount) for display, determine +/- from sign of amount
- Amounts are already signed in the DB (negative = expense) — never store a separate type field. category_id is stored on transactions and recurring_rules.
- Date format for DB: yyyy-MM-dd (use date-fns format())
- Date format for display: use date-fns format() with human-readable patterns
- The FAB lives in app/(app)/layout.tsx and is positioned with bottom-[calc(56px+env(safe-area-inset-bottom,0px)+12px)] — never move it inside a transformed ancestor

## File Structure

### Routes
- app/(app)/ — protected app pages (calendar, transactions, add, settings, analytics)
- app/login/ — public auth page (signup + signin + forgot-password); optional `NEXT_PUBLIC_INVITE_CODE` gate
- app/invite/[token]/ — public invite acceptance page (outside `(app)` group; whitelisted in proxy.ts); validates token server-side via service role
- app/auth/callback/ — PKCE code-exchange handler; redirects to `?next=` param; used by password-reset and invite signup flows
- app/reset-password/ — public; requires active recovery session set by auth/callback
- app/api/delete-account/ — authenticated POST; deletes all user data in FK-safe order then removes auth user via admin client

### Key lib files
- lib/api.ts — SWR fetchers: `fetchAccounts`, `fetchCalendarData(month, year, accountId)`, `fetchTransactions(accountId)`, `fetchTransaction`, `fetchRecurringRule`, `fetchCategories(accountId)`, `fetchPendingInvitations(accountId)`, `fetchCategoryUsageCount`
- lib/swr-keys.ts — all SWR key functions: `calendarMonthSwrKey`, `transactionsSwrKey`, `categoriesSwrKey`, `membersSwrKey`, `pendingInvitationsSwrKey`, `accountsSwrKey`
- lib/swr-invalidate.ts — `invalidateNext12CalendarMonths(accountId)`
- lib/transactions-mutations.ts — all mutations: deleteTransaction, skipRecurringOccurrence, endRecurringRuleFuture, updateTransaction, createTransaction, createRecurringRule, upsertModifiedRecurringException, moveRecurringOccurrence, applyRecurringEditFromDate, updateRecurringSegmentInPlace, splitRecurringRuleAtDate, makeTransactionRecurring, recalibrateBalance, createCategory, updateCategory, deleteCategory, createAccount, updateAccount, deleteBudget, createInvitation, revokeInvitation, removeMember, leaveAccount
- lib/member-actions.ts — `"use server"`; `getAccountMembers(accountId)` uses service role; access-gated to budget members
- lib/invite-actions.ts — `"use server"`; `acceptInvitation(token)` uses service role; repeats all security checks server-side
- lib/validation.ts — Zod schemas + `safeParseMutation()`; `uuidSchema.parse()` sanitizes IDs before PostgREST `.or()` interpolation (injection prevention)
- lib/types.ts — all shared TypeScript types (Transaction, RecurringRule, RecurringException, Account, Category, AccountMember, BudgetInvitation, etc.)
- lib/projection.ts — balance projection engine; pure function — account-scoping enforced upstream by callers
- lib/recurring-rules.ts — `mapRecurringRuleRow()` (DB row → RecurringRule); `getRecurringRuleIdAndDate(id)` (parses synthetic `${ruleId}-${date}` IDs)
- lib/url.ts — `withActiveAccountQuery(path, accountId)` appends `?account=` to deep links
- lib/user-display.ts — `getUserDisplayInitials`, `getUserGivenNameFromMetadata` for auth `user_metadata`

### Key components
- components/active-account-provider.tsx — `useActiveAccount()`; resolution order: `?account=` URL param → localStorage `budget-buddy:active-account` → first account; `setActiveAccount` writes localStorage only
- components/budget-members-section.tsx — budget sharing UI; owner-only controls gated by `role === "owner"`
- hooks/use-edit-loader.ts — guards edit loads by `expectedAccountId`; shows budget-mismatch error instead of pre-filling cross-account data
- proxy.ts — edge auth; unauthenticated → /login; authenticated away from /login → `?next=` or `/`; `/invite/*` whitelisted public

## Key Rules

- Mobile-first always — design for 390px width, scale up for desktop
- A first account is auto-created on signup via a database trigger; users can then create additional budgets in `/settings`. New accounts default `starting_balance = 0` if the user leaves it blank. After a `createAccount`, the UI immediately switches the active budget to the new id.
- Submit on `/add` remains disabled when `activeAccountId` is absent as a silent safety net for the rare zero-account state. Calendar and settings render an explicit "Create your first budget" CTA instead of a blank screen.
- Active budget id MUST be threaded through every account-scoped mutation invalidation (use `transactionsSwrKey(accountId)`, `calendarMonthSwrKey(month, year, accountId)`, `invalidateNext12CalendarMonths(accountId)`). Never invalidate by raw string keys like `"transactions"`.
- Never revert the SWR data fetching pattern back to server-side fetching
- Recurring edit scope: "this and all future" → `applyRecurringEditFromDate`; "just this" (same date) → `upsertModifiedRecurringException`; "just this" (date change) → `moveRecurringOccurrence` (skip original + one-time on new date — deleting that one-time later does NOT restore the original, the skip remains); skip → `skipRecurringOccurrence`; end → `endRecurringRuleFuture`; convert one-time to recurring → `makeTransactionRecurring`. Never call `splitRecurringRuleAtDate` or `updateRecurringSegmentInPlace` directly from UI.
- deleteCategory relies on DB-level FK behavior (ON DELETE SET NULL) to null out category_id references on transactions and recurring_rules. Verify this is configured in Supabase if categories are deletable.
- deleteBudget relies on DB-level ON DELETE CASCADE: deleting an accounts row cascades to recurring_rules (which cascades to recurring_exceptions) and transactions. Migration 20260429000000_account_cascade_deletes.sql adds these constraints.
- Swipe gestures use react-swipeable with preventScrollOnSwipe: true — always include this to avoid conflicting with vertical scroll
- Recurring transaction synthetic id format: `${ruleId}-${date}` — parse with id.slice(0, -11) for ruleId and id.slice(-10) for date
- recurring_exceptions with type 'skip' are used to hide individual occurrences — never use a cancelling transaction for this purpose
- PWA layout uses a flex column shell (animated-gradient, min-h-screen, flex flex-col) with an inner scrollable div (flex-1, overflow-y-auto). Never use h-fill-available, min-h-fill-available, or overflow: hidden on html/body — these cause PWA layout bugs on iOS
- Safe area insets are applied once: pt-[env(safe-area-inset-top,0px)] on the content div, pb-[calc(56px+env(safe-area-inset-bottom,0px))] on the content div, pb-[env(safe-area-inset-bottom,0px)] on the nav inner div, and pb-[env(safe-area-inset-bottom,0px)] on any bottom drawer/sheet
- Nav height is always 56px (--nav-height: 56px) — safe area is handled separately, never baked into --nav-height
- Never apply safe area padding more than once on the same visual element — stacking causes nav/drawer to be too tall on iPhone
- Security headers (X-Frame-Options, HSTS, CSP, etc.) are configured in `next.config.mjs` `headers()`. When adding external scripts, fonts, stylesheets, or API endpoints, update the CSP directives (especially `script-src`, `connect-src`, `font-src`) or the new resource will be blocked in production

## Code Cleanliness Rules

These rules apply to every change Cursor makes. No exceptions.

### Imports

- Never add an import that isn't used in the file
- When removing a feature or component, remove its import too
- Do not import types that are already available from @/lib/types

### CSS / Tailwind

- Never add a CSS class to globals.css without using it in a .tsx file in the same change
- When removing a component or styling pattern, remove its CSS class from globals.css too
- Prefer Tailwind utility classes over custom CSS classes unless the style is reused 3+ times
- Never add inline styles unless backdrop-filter or other CSS properties aren't supported by Tailwind

### Props & Types

- Never define a prop in an interface that isn't used by the component
- When refactoring a component, remove props that are no longer needed from both the interface and all call sites
- Never duplicate a type that already exists in @/lib/types — import it instead

### Dead Code

- Never leave commented-out code in files
- Never leave TODO comments without an associated issue or note in the PR
- When replacing a pattern (e.g. skeleton loading → animations), remove the old pattern entirely in the same change
- Never leave console.log statements in committed code

### Component Rules

- Never create a new component for something used only once — inline it instead
- Never leave a component file that isn't imported anywhere
- When removing a page or route, remove its loading.tsx, error.tsx, and any associated components too

### Reusability & Maintainability

- Before writing any JSX pattern, check if a similar component already exists
  in components/ — use or extend it instead of writing a new one.
- If the same UI pattern (error state, empty state, card layout, section header,
  button group) appears in 2+ files, extract it into a shared component before
  adding a third instance.
- If the same className string (3+ Tailwind classes) is copy-pasted in 3+ places,
  extract it into a shared component or CSS utility.
- When creating a new shared component, find and replace all existing inline
  instances of that pattern in the same change — never leave old duplicates behind.
- Prefer composable components with clear props over context-specific one-off markup.
- If updating a UI pattern requires touching more than one file, it should be a
  shared component.

### State Management Rules

- Never put more than 5 useState calls in a single component without grouping
  related state into useReducer or a custom hook first
- If 3+ state values always change together, they belong in a useReducer or a
  single state object — not separate useState calls
- If a useEffect block is longer than 15 lines or sets more than 3 state values,
  extract it into a custom hook
- Local form state belongs in the component (useState or useReducer) — never in
  global state (Jotai, Context, etc.)
- Shared cross-component state that isn't server data belongs in Jotai atoms in
  lib/atoms/ — not prop-drilled or duplicated
- Never duplicate state shape across two components — extract a shared hook
  instead (e.g. useRecurringScope used by both add page and day-sheet)
- Custom hooks live in hooks/ and are named use-[feature].ts

### Component Size Rules

- If a component exceeds 200 lines, consider splitting it
- If a component has more than one distinct "mode" (e.g. add vs edit, actions
  vs edit drawer), consider whether each mode should be its own component
- A component that requires reading more than 3 other files to understand is too
  coupled — simplify its dependencies
- Page components (app/(app)/**/page.tsx) should be thin — data fetching and
  state logic belong in hooks, not inline in the page

### General

- Every change should leave the codebase cleaner than before
- If a refactor requires touching more than 5 files, flag it and list the files before making changes
- Never silently fix unrelated code while making a targeted change — flag it separately instead
- After any change that affects the Supabase schema, file structure, exported functions, key behaviors, or design system tokens, update .cursorrules to reflect the change in the same commit. Never let .cursorrules become stale.
